- New tests:
  - Evaluate module, cache all results. Change one param value to a DIFFERENT value → dependent nodes re-evaluate, non-dependent don't
  - Change a param that feeds a `let` whose expression result is unchanged (e.g., `let x = if a > 0 then 1 else 1`, change a) → early cutoff prevents downstream re-evaluation
  - Version fast path: evaluate same snapshot twice → second time hits cache for all nodes
  - Cache miss on first evaluation (cold start)

## Context
When a parameter changes, not all nodes need re-evaluation — only those that are both "dirty" (transitively depend on the changed value) AND "demanded" (someone cares about their result). The dirty∩demand intersection is the minimal re-evaluation set. A sequential scheduler processes this set in priority order.

## What to implement

1. **DemandRegistry** in `crates/reify-eval/src/demand.rs` (new file):
   ```rust
   pub struct DemandRegistry {
       /// Nodes that are always demanded (e.g., visible geometry, active constraints)
       always_demanded: HashSet&lt;NodeId&gt;,
       /// Backward transitive closure of demanded nodes (cached, rebuilt on topology change)
       demand_cone: HashSet&lt;NodeId&gt;,
   }

   impl DemandRegistry {
       pub fn new() -> Self;
       pub fn add_demand(&amp;mut self, node: NodeId);
       pub fn remove_demand(&amp;mut self, node: NodeId);
       pub fn rebuild_cone(&amp;mut self, reverse_index: &amp;ReverseDependencyIndex, graph: &amp;EvaluationGraph);
       pub fn is_demanded(&amp;self, node: &amp;NodeId) -> bool;
   }
   ```
   The demand cone is the set of all nodes that transitively feed into a demanded node. It's computed by walking backward from demanded nodes through forward dependency edges.

2. **Dirty cone computation** in `crates/reify-eval/src/dirty.rs` (new file):
   ```rust
   /// Given a set of changed ValueCells, compute the dirty cone:
   /// all nodes that transitively depend on any changed cell.
   pub fn compute_dirty_cone(
       changed: &amp;HashSet&lt;ValueCellId&gt;,
       reverse_index: &amp;ReverseDependencyIndex,
   ) -> HashSet&lt;NodeId&gt;;
   ```
   Walk forward from changed cells through the reverse dependency index.

3. **Intersection** — the minimal re-evaluation set:
   ```rust
   pub fn compute_eval_set(
       dirty: &amp;HashSet&lt;NodeId&gt;,
       demand: &amp;DemandRegistry,
   ) -> Vec&lt;NodeId&gt;;
   ```
   Returns `dirty ∩ demand_cone`, sorted by evaluation order (dependencies first).

4. **Sequential scheduler** in `crates/reify-runtime/src/lib.rs`:
   ```rust
   pub struct SequentialScheduler;

   impl SequentialScheduler {
       /// Process the evaluation set in dependency order.
       /// Returns the set of nodes whose results actually changed.
       pub fn execute(
           &amp;self,
           eval_set: Vec&lt;NodeId&gt;,
           // ... evaluation context (snapshot, cache, etc.)
       ) -> HashSet&lt;NodeId&gt;;
   }
   ```
   For M2, this is a simple loop: evaluate each node in order, applying early cutoff to shrink the remaining set dynamically.

5. **Topological sort** — ensure eval_set is ordered so dependencies evaluate before dependents:
   ```rust
   pub fn topological_sort(
       nodes: &amp;HashSet&lt;NodeId&gt;,
       traces: &amp;HashMap&lt;NodeId, DependencyTrace&gt;,
   ) -> Vec&lt;NodeId&gt;;
   ```

